<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1436,1948,2011]" lastBlockId="39.[151,1437,150,213]" lastPageId="39" lastPageNumber="440" pageId="38" pageNumber="439">
The examination of photographs of the 
<typeStatus box="[593,691,1948,1974]" pageId="38" pageNumber="439">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hedley &amp; May" baseAuthorityYear="1908" box="[728,898,1948,1974]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Leptochitonidae" genus="Leptochiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidopleurida" pageId="38" pageNumber="439" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="columnarius">
<emphasis box="[728,898,1948,1974]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="439">L. columnarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
indicated that the antemucronal slope of the tail valve is one and a half times longer than the postmucronal slope. This is probably why this species was later placed in the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thiele" authorityYear="1909" box="[294,420,151,177]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Leptochitonidae" genus="Parachiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidopleurida" pageId="39" pageNumber="440" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[294,420,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="440">Parachiton</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Iredale &amp; Hull (1925). 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hedley &amp; May" baseAuthorityYear="1908" box="[722,891,151,177]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Leptochitonidae" genus="Leptochiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidopleurida" pageId="39" pageNumber="440" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="columnarius">
<emphasis box="[722,891,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="440">L. columnarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Kaas &amp; Van Belle" authorityYear="1994" box="[1095,1289,151,177]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Leptochitonidae" genus="Leptochiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidopleurida" pageId="39" pageNumber="440" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="subantarcticus">
<emphasis box="[1095,1289,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="440">L. subantarcticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its highly or very highly arched valves, but differs from the latter by having a posterior mucro.
</paragraph>
